                <section id="wattage" class="mb-16">
                    <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">3. Output Wattage: How Fast Should It Charge?</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">mAh tells you <em>how much</em> power. Wattage tells you <em>how fast</em> it delivers that power. Both matter equally.</p>
                    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
                        <table class="w-full border border-slate-200 rounded-xl">
                            <thead class="bg-brandBlue text-white">
                                <tr>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Output Wattage</th>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Charges</th>
                                    <th class="text-left p-3 font-black uppercase text-xs">Example Use</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">10-12W (5V/2A)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Basic USB-A charging. Slow — a phone takes 2-3 hours.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Earbuds, smartwatch, emergency backup</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">18-20W (USB-C PD)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Fast charging for most phones. iPhone 0-50% in ~30 min.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Daily phone charging</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold text-brandBlue">30W (USB-C PD + PPS)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Optimal for Samsung (45W PPS) and latest iPhones (~27W).</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Flagship phone fast charging ★</td></tr>
                                <tr class="border-t border-slate-200"><td class="p-3 font-bold">45-65W (USB-C PD 3.0)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Charges ultrabooks and tablets at full speed.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Phone + tablet/laptop simultaneously</td></tr>
                                <tr><td class="p-3 font-bold">100W+ (PD 3.1)</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Full laptop charging. MacBook Pro 16" at full speed.</td><td class="p-3 text-slate-600 text-sm">Laptop replacement charger</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-brandBlue/10 border-l-4 border-brandBlue p-5 rounded-r-xl">
                        <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Key Rule: Your Device Sets the Speed Limit</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">A 100W power bank won't charge an iPhone faster than a 30W bank — the iPhone caps at ~27W regardless of the power source. Always check your device's maximum charging speed before paying for wattage you can't use. For most smartphone-only users, <strong>20-30W output is the practical sweet spot</strong>.</p>
                    </div>
